article.headline: Garnett, Szczerbiak steal thunder from Payton

images.name: Payton_Gary 030224 Inline
images.caption: Gary Payton helped the Bucks rally late, finishing with 21 points, but he couldn't get his new team over the top.

article.linkText: T-Wolves too much for Bucks, and Payton
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Kevin Garnett and Wally Szczerbiak made sure Gary Payton didn't enjoy his home debut. Garnett had 34 points, 12 rebounds and eight assists as the Minnesota Timberwolves beat the Milwaukee Bucks 117-114 Monday night in Payton's first game in Milwaukee since joining the team. Szczerbiak made all 12 of his free throws and added 26 points for Minnesota, which has won four in a row and 10 of 11 overall. Garnett and Szczerbiak combined to score 13 of the Timberwolves' final 16 points. ''With Gary here now, they're a little more edgy, a little more aggressive, a little more feisty,'' Garnett said. ''If I was to credit anything, it was our defense. Our defense is what's winning games for us.'' Minnesota led 89-72 at the start of the fourth quarter and took a 112-104 lead when Troy Hudson made two free throws with 43.2 seconds left. But Milwaukee rallied, tying a season high with 42 points in the fourth, and cut the lead to two, 116-114, when Sam Cassell stole an inbounds pass and fed Desmond Mason for a layup with two seconds left. Hudson, who had 21 points, made one free throw and Garnett stole the inbounds pass to seal the victory. Garnett, averaging 28.2 points and 14.2 rebounds in February, now has an NBA-best 47 double-doubles. He was also 12-for-16 from the free-throw line. ''We were able to exploit some things inside,'' said Minnesota coach Flip Saunders. ''We've got an MVP player in Garnett that's playing at an extremely high level, and Wally's playing like an All-Star.'' Payton, a nine-time All-Star, finished with a team-high 21 points and nine assists. It was his first game in Milwaukee since he and Mason were traded from Seattle on Thursday in exchange for Ray Allen, Kevin Ollie, Ronald Murray and a conditional 2003 draft pick. In his first game with the Bucks, a 93-90 victory at Portland on Saturday, Payton led the Bucks with 22 points. ''I think we all know we've got to play a little better defense than what we're doing,'' Payton said. ''We play better defense we win this basketball game.'' It was Minnesota's eighth consecutive victory over Milwaukee. The Bucks, who lost for the fifth time in six games, also got 19 points from Michael Redd and 18 points and seven assists from Cassell. ''It's a loss, and it's always hard to feel good about a loss,'' Milwaukee coach George Karl said. ''In general, it's one of those games we'll see on film some good and some bad. We'll work on a couple of things, get Payton and Desmond feeling a little more comfortable and go to work on Wednesday.'' Minnesota closed out the second quarter with a 22-8 run to lead at halftime, 60-51. Game notes
Szczerbiak is averaging 25.3 points a game over his last three games. ... Both teams combined to shoot 17 of 18 from the free-throw line in the first half. Minnesota was 13-for-14 and finished with 19 more free throw attempts than Milwaukee for the game. ''That's extremely disappointing,'' Karl said. ''(The referees) don't seem to respect us.'' ... The Bucks' bench outscored Minnesota's 49-9. ... Minnesota won its seventh game in a row in the Bradley Center. The last time Milwaukee won a home game against the Timberwolves was Feb. 8, 1995. ... Minnesota is 33-1 when leading or tied after the third quarter. ... The reunited tandem of Karl and Payton entered the game with a regular-season record of 25-1 against Minnesota (1992-'98). ... Minnesota has already set a franchise record for February victories (10-1) and needs to finish 1-1 to post its highest monthly winning percentage (12-3 in January, 2000). ... The Timberwolves won their seventh consecutive game against an Eastern opponent.
